<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-10-28T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-10-28T22:00:00-05:00" n="685" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d685">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/429: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-10-29T11:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">October 29,
                                        1926—11 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 29—1:03
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>519. Following from American consul general, Canton: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“October 28, 1 p.m. Guise of preventing traffic in opium, Chen
                                    announces the establishment by the Ministry of Finance of
                                    inspection stations at Dosing and Hotow, West River, at which
                                    all passing steamers of every nationality are required to stop
                                    and undergo inspection. Portuguese consul favors joint protest
                                    immediately, but the other interested consuls prefer first
                                    consulting their respective Legations. Despatch will be
                                    forwarded.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>